{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1407"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1407"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.1,0.15,0.04,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86176"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2038"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"6445"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28373"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is seen by a Urologist after a firm, nodular prostate is found on digital rectal examination by his General Practitioner. He has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. His medications list includes amlodipine and atorvastatin. He is otherwise in good health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA biopsy is arranged and shows a Gleason score of 3+3=6. Staging MRI and PSMA PET scans confirm T2bN0M0 prostate cancer. Upon discussion of management options, he expresses concern on the potential long-term side effects of the treatments, particularly the impact any of these might have on his sexual life. He wants to know what will provide the best balance of the risk of his cancer spread and maintenance of sexual function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan given the investigation results and personal priorities?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nerve sparing radical prostatectomy","Low dose rate brachytherapy","External beam radiation therapy","Androgen deprivation therapy","Active surveillance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s low grade of prostate cancer (thus lower chance of metastasis) and concerns with regards to sexual dysfunction, he should be offered \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E.  The patient\u0027s age and willingness to have frequent biopsies and blood tests for monitoring must be assured for active surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErectile dysfunction (ED) is known to be a common complication of radical treatment for prostate cancer. Treatment for prostate cancer can affect erectile function through the following main mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELibido - decreased by hormonal therapy which decreases serum testosterone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMechanical ability - impacted by neurovascular damage during surgery or radiotherapy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEjaculation - impacted through surgery, where the seminal vesicles are removed with the prostate; and with radiotherapy, where scarring and fibrosis of the prostate and seminal vesicles leads to ejaculatory dysfunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of the options provided, other than \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E, carry a risk of ED. \u003Cstrong\u003EAndrogen deprivation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with very high rates of ED due to lowered levels of serum testosterone resulting in a decreased frequency of nocturnal erections, as well as decreased rigidity, duration and volume of erection, in addition to the loss of libido and potential inability to attain orgasm. \u003Cstrong\u003EExternal beam radiation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is also associated with high rates of ED, although the presentation is often delayed as the nerves die off over 3-4 years. \u003Cstrong\u003EBrachytherapy\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly high dose rate, also has a high rate of ED. The rates of ED following \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical prostatectomy\u003C/strong\u003E depend on the type of procedure, preoperative sexual function, patient age, and stage and bulk of disease. Bilateral nerve-sparing prostatectomy provides the lowest risk with approximately 70% of patients able to penetrate for intercourse, as opposed to 40% when unilateral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptions in the management of ED in patients who have been treated for prostate cancer include medications, mechanical devices such as the vacuum constriction device or vacuum pump, and the surgical insertion of a penile implant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance carries the lowest risk of erectile dysfunction following treatment for prostate cancer.","Prostate cancer management should balance cancer control with quality of life, including sexual function.","Erectile dysfunction is a common complication of radical treatment for prostate cancer."],"references":["Akbal C, Tinay I, Sim\u015fek F, Turkeri LN. Erectile dysfunction following radiotherapy and brachytherapy for prostate cancer: Pathophysiology, prevention and treatment. Int Urol Nephrol. 2008;40(2):355-63. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17960489/#:~:text=Although%20arterial%20damage%20seems%20to,in%20the%20etiology%20of%20ED.","Bratu O, Oprea I, Marcu D, Spinu D, Niculae A, et al. Erectile dysfunction post-radical prostatectomy - a challenge for both patient and physician. J Med Life. 2017;10(1):13-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5304365/","Shpot EV, Chinenov DV, Amosov AV, Chernov YN, Yurova MV, Lerner YV. Erectile dysfunction associated with radical prostatectomy: appropriateness and methods to preserve potency. Urologiia. 2018;2:75-82. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29901298/","White ID, Wilson J, Aslet P, Baxter AB, Birtle A, Challacombe B, et al. Development of UK guidance on the management of erectile dysfunction resulting from radical radiotherapy and androgen deprivation therapy for prostate cancer. Int J Clin Pract. 2015;69(1):106-23. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4309408/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86176"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86176"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T15:41:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T15:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ